x7qxLc6l04suWewvTZzEXsav.text: Database management systems provide functionality that is central to developing business applications. Therefore, database management systems are increasingly being used as an important component in applications. Yet, the problem of tuning database management systems for achieving required performance is significant, and results in high total cost of ownership (TCO). The goal of our research in the AutoAdmin project is to make database systems self-tuning and self-administering. We achieve this by enabling databases to track the usage of their systems and to gracefully adapt to application requirements. Thus, instead of applications having to track and tune databases, databases actively auto-tunes itself to be responsive to application needs. Our research has led to novel self-tuning components being included in Microsoft SQL Server
